{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639488"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:05:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:05:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17774"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17774"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.9,0.05,0,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72416"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10488"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57886"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7325"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24525"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72416"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old cyclist injures his left hand when he falls off his bicycle. An X-ray shows a fracture of his scaphoid (Image). If left untreated, there are a number of potential complications following this type of fracture.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most serious complication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Avascular necrosis","Carpal tunnel syndrome","Chronic pain","Non-union","Osteoarthritis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn untreated scaphoid fracture can lead to \u003Cstrong\u003Eavascular necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E of the proximal pole of the scaphoid. This is due to the unique blood supply of the scaphoid, which is primarily retrograde, meaning that the blood supply enters distally and flows proximally. If the fracture disrupts this blood supply, the proximal fragment may not receive adequate blood flow, leading to necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-union\u003C/strong\u003E is another potential complication of a scaphoid fracture, especially if it is not immobilised properly. However, avascular necrosis is considered more serious because it can lead to collapse of the bone and subsequent wrist dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can develop as a long-term consequence of a scaphoid fracture, particularly if there is non-union or avascular necrosis. However, it is a secondary complication that arises from these primary issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic pain\u003C/strong\u003E are less common complications of scaphoid fractures and are not as directly related to the fracture itself as avascular necrosis is.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A scaphoid fracture, if left untreated, can lead to avascular necrosis due to its unique blood supply.","The proximal pole of the scaphoid is at risk of avascular necrosis because it relies on retrograde blood flow.","Early diagnosis and treatment of scaphoid fractures are crucial to prevent long-term complications."],"references":["Davies PSE, Cox QGN. Avascular necrosis and fracture of the scaphoid in a child followed by non-union. J Hand Surg Eur Vol. 2019 Jan;44(1):109-110. doi: 10.1177/1753193418793574. Epub 2018 Aug 22. PMID: 30134748.","Tokyay A, Gunal I. Avascular necrosis of the distal pole of the scaphoid. Case Reports Plast Surg Hand Surg. 2015 Jan 20;2(2):40-2. doi: 10.3109/23320885.2015.1006633. PMID: 27252968; PMCID: PMC4623543.","Amundsen A, Oh C, Huang TCT, Cantwell S, Hsu CC, Moran SL. Avascular Necrosis of the Scaphoid-Preiser Disease: Outcomes of 39 Surgical Cases. J Hand Surg Am. 2023 Mar;48(3):313.e1-313.e9. doi: 10.1016/j.jhsa.2021.10.023. Epub 2021 Dec 6. PMID: 34887136."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57886"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17774"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21352"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21352"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8CEEOoQxWHhB4gRF9mRrZbPqeMhVoP.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8CEEOoQxWHhB4gRF9mRrZbPqeMhVoP.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":263,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57886"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T17:00:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T17:01:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10488"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72416"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt